\n","plt.scatter(X[inlier_mask], y[inlier_mask],\n","            c='steelblue', edgecolor='white',\n","            marker='o', label='Inliers')\n","\n","plt.scatter(X[outlier_mask], y[outlier_mask],\n","            c='limegreen', edgecolor='white',\n","            marker='s', label='Outliers')\n","\n","plt.plot(line_X, line_y_ransac, color='black', lw=2)\n","plt.xlabel('Living area above ground in square feet')\n","plt.ylabel('Sale price in U.S. dollars')\n","plt.legend(loc='upper left')\n","plt.tight_layout()\n","plt.show()"],"outputs":[{"output_type":"display_data","data":{"text/plain":["<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"],"image/png":"\n"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":6,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/","height":487},"id":"fOdC4XG9_9Mg","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1781858261742,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":438,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"b023d0c8-d35a-4b0f-9836-16988d973e43"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["## 3. Extracting Model Parameters and Adjusting Thresholds\n","\n","We can inspect the slope and intercept of the resulting robust regression line. You'll likely notice it differs slightly from a standard linear regression model fitted on the exact same dataset without RANSAC."],"metadata":{"id":"dmIBKOB2_9Mg"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["print(f'Slope: {ransac.estimator_.coef_[0]:.3f}')\n","print(f'Intercept: {ransac.estimator_.intercept_:.3f}')"],"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["Slope: 106.451\n","Intercept: 20133.205\n"]}],"execution_count":7,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"p0b9AB9x_9Mg","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1781858265636,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":8,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"c3a25302-dd45-4306-814a-9433bb33f333"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["### Understanding and Adjusting the MAD\n","\n","The threshold for what constitutes an inlier versus an outlier is problem-specific. We can compute the MAD for our dataset manually to understand the default threshold RANSAC is using:"],"metadata":{"id":"E1g-eYVN_9Mg"}},{"cell_type":"code","source":["def median_absolute_deviation(data):\n","    return np.median(np.abs(data - np.median(data)))\n","\n","print(median_absolute_deviation(y))"],"outputs":[{"output_type":"stream","name":"stdout","text":["37000.0\n"]}],"execution_count":8,"metadata":{"colab":{"base_uri":"https://localhost:8080/"},"id":"YMjsyYIV_9Mh","executionInfo":{"status":"ok","timestamp":1781858268951,"user_tz":-330,"elapsed":47,"user":{"displayName":"Gobisan Ananthanadarajan","userId":"08370486503672403873"}},"outputId":"046233f6-a5f9-4c35-e1a5-10001bd5722d"}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":["If we want to identify *fewer* data points as outliers, we can manually supply a `residual_threshold` value that is greater than the MAD (for example, setting `residual_threshold=65000`).\n","\n","*Note: While RANSAC reduces the potential effect of outliers on the training data, you must still evaluate the regression model using standard performance metrics to ensure it actually improves predictive performance on unseen data.*"],"metadata":{"id":"0fCtajbs_9Mh"}}],"metadata":{"colab":{"provenance":[]},"kernelspec":{"display_name":"Python 3","name":"python3"}},"nbformat":4,"nbformat_minor":0}